00:47:54.770 --> 00:47:57.120
in her late 40s or early 50s.

00:47:57.120 --> 00:47:58.720
Actually a strange
part of that story

00:47:58.720 --> 00:48:02.560
is that after about nine months,
because this was so powerful

00:48:02.560 --> 00:48:05.540
for me, I wanted to go
back and see her and thank

00:48:05.540 --> 00:48:07.310
her and connect with her.

00:48:07.310 --> 00:48:09.874
And I went back
to the strip mall.

00:48:09.874 --> 00:48:12.540
And there was a fence around it,
and all the stores were closed.

00:48:12.540 --> 00:48:13.360
And it was very strange.

00:48:13.360 --> 00:48:14.470
This was in the high desert.

00:48:14.470 --> 00:48:16.303
And if you've ever lived
in the high desert,

00:48:16.303 --> 00:48:18.630
in the wee evenings
the skies can sort of

00:48:18.630 --> 00:48:22.210
get this dark blue
with different shades

00:48:22.210 --> 00:48:23.560
and wispy clouds.

00:48:23.560 --> 00:48:25.689
And I used to drive this
orange Stingray bike.

00:48:25.689 --> 00:48:27.980
And I pulled up there, and
I was reflecting on the fact

00:48:27.980 --> 00:48:29.320
that it was gone.

00:48:29.320 --> 00:48:31.290
She had completely disappeared.

00:48:31.290 --> 00:48:33.815
And as I'm sitting there on my
bike and thinking about this,

00:48:33.815 --> 00:48:37.520
this big tumbleweed
blows into my bicycle.

00:48:37.520 --> 00:48:39.240
It was like almost
this TV moment.

00:48:39.240 --> 00:48:41.230
But no, I never saw her again.

00:48:41.230 --> 00:48:46.130
Now, to research this book,
though, because many of us

00:48:46.130 --> 00:48:49.270
don't appreciate that our
memories can-- even though we

00:48:49.270 --> 00:48:51.180
have a clear memory
of something--

00:48:51.180 --> 00:48:54.280
can often not be real.

00:48:54.280 --> 00:48:56.260
And in fact, a wonderful
example-- there's

00:48:56.260 --> 00:48:58.660
a woman who used to tell a
story that her father died

00:48:58.660 --> 00:48:59.680
when she was 10.

00:48:59.680 --> 00:49:01.430
And she would go around
telling everybody,

00:49:01.430 --> 00:49:03.620
you know, I keep my
father in my heart.

00:49:03.620 --> 00:49:06.875
Because every night he would
read the same story to me.

00:49:06.875 --> 00:49:09.125
And then at some point, she
was telling somebody that,

00:49:09.125 --> 00:49:10.400
and she goes,
that's not possible.

00:49:10.400 --> 00:49:11.630
She goes, what are
you talking about?

00:49:11.630 --> 00:49:13.046
She says, well,
the author who did

00:49:13.046 --> 00:49:15.410
that story didn't write
it until five years

00:49:15.410 --> 00:49:18.170
after your father died.

00:49:18.170 --> 00:49:20.880
But she created a
narrative in her head.

00:49:20.880 --> 00:49:24.430
So actually at one point, as I
was going back and reflecting

00:49:24.430 --> 00:49:26.800
on all of my interactions
with this woman, I'm going,

00:49:26.800 --> 00:49:27.840
did I just make this up?

00:49:30.630 --> 00:49:32.595
And so I actually
got it investigated.

00:49:32.595 --> 00:49:33.470
And we researched it.

00:49:33.470 --> 00:49:36.730
We tracked down the grandson.

00:49:36.730 --> 00:49:40.210
And in fact, he said she was
exactly like I described.

00:49:40.210 --> 00:49:42.380
And she had had sort
of this background.

00:49:42.380 --> 00:49:44.160
And what's interesting
about this,

00:49:44.160 --> 00:49:48.420
though it's sad in some
ways, is that the guy who

00:49:48.420 --> 00:49:51.770
owned the store-- he had
divorced his wife and the son

00:49:51.770 --> 00:49:53.580
lived with the wife.

00:49:53.580 --> 00:49:57.370
And that summer that
child who was my age

00:49:57.370 --> 00:50:01.360
was supposed to be with
them during the summer.

00:50:01.360 --> 00:50:03.330
And the parents got
into a big argument,

00:50:03.330 --> 00:50:06.500
and the mother
refused to send him.

00:50:06.500 --> 00:50:13.090
So I think I probably got the
benefit of that interaction.

