And this is why fundamentally
in every religious practice,

00:53:32.560 --> 00:53:36.360
compassion is at the base.

00:53:36.360 --> 00:53:38.550
Because it's so, so important.

00:53:38.550 --> 00:53:40.850
If you look-- not only
for the individual, which,

00:53:40.850 --> 00:53:42.620
in some ways, is what
we're talking about today--

00:53:42.620 --> 00:53:44.578
but if you look at the
educational environment,

00:53:44.578 --> 00:53:50.990
a variety of studies that
with intent put compassion

00:53:50.990 --> 00:53:54.500
in the forefront, in the
educational environment

00:53:54.500 --> 00:53:57.080
with mindfulness
types of practices,

00:53:57.080 --> 00:53:59.650
this is having a significant
effect on attendance

00:53:59.650 --> 00:54:06.227
and academic performance
and decreasing violence.

00:54:06.227 --> 00:54:08.060
Now we're still at the
early stages of this,

00:54:08.060 --> 00:54:09.100
so I don't want
to make a blanket

00:54:09.100 --> 00:54:11.130
statement that jeez, mindfulness
is great for everything.

00:54:11.130 --> 00:54:12.100
Because it's not.

00:54:12.100 --> 00:54:15.870
And mindfulness alone without
compassion definitely is not.

00:54:15.870 --> 00:54:18.319
But in general in regard to
the educational environment,

00:54:18.319 --> 00:54:20.110
if we look at the health
care environment--

00:54:20.110 --> 00:54:23.790
I just did a paper and a
blog in the "Huffington Post"

00:54:23.790 --> 00:54:26.310
called "Why Kindness Heals."

00:54:26.310 --> 00:54:29.110
And I even tell my residents
that even though I'm

00:54:29.110 --> 00:54:31.750
in a very technologically
sophisticated specialty

00:54:31.750 --> 00:54:36.090
such as neurosurgery, my
successes, my outcomes,

00:54:36.090 --> 00:54:40.290
are just as much affected by
my connecting with the patient.

00:54:40.290 --> 00:54:41.830
And all of you have
been to doctors.

00:54:41.830 --> 00:54:43.350
The worst doctor you
can have is somebody

00:54:43.350 --> 00:54:45.450
who doesn't look you in
the eye, who is brusque,

00:54:45.450 --> 00:54:46.980
sort of looking around here.

00:54:46.980 --> 00:54:50.390
You know he wants to be
somebody else or someplace else.

00:54:50.390 --> 00:54:54.390
But if you see a doctor
who leans forward,

00:54:54.390 --> 00:54:56.890
who touches you, who
says, take your time.

00:54:56.890 --> 00:54:58.744
I want to understand
what's going on.

00:54:58.744 --> 00:54:59.660
It changes everything.

00:54:59.660 --> 00:55:01.920
Because you're shifting
from the stressful mode

00:55:01.920 --> 00:55:04.400
you're in, because seeing
a doctor is stressful,

00:55:04.400 --> 00:55:07.180
to one of calmness and
being with somebody

00:55:07.180 --> 00:55:09.120
who you feel you can
be authentic with,

00:55:09.120 --> 00:55:10.430
who you can trust.

00:55:10.430 --> 00:55:11.640
And that calms everything.

00:55:11.640 --> 00:55:13.190
In fact, we're just
beginning a study

00:55:13.190 --> 00:55:15.970
on how these types of
practices affect wound

00:55:15.970 --> 00:55:18.250
healing in surgical patients.

00:55:18.250 --> 00:55:22.030
And we actually have a grant
with Dignity Health where we're

00:55:22.030 --> 00:55:25.500
actually looking at how all
of these different types

00:55:25.500 --> 00:55:29.240
of engagements not only affect
patient outcomes, readmission

00:55:29.240 --> 00:55:34.140
rates, wound healing, et cetera,
but also how you can decrease

00:55:34.140 --> 00:55:36.400
health care worker burnout.

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:39.230
And we're also doing
these practices

00:55:39.230 --> 00:55:41.110
with some of the
medical students as well

00:55:41.110 --> 00:55:42.010
as the residents.

00:55:42.010 --> 00:55:43.490
So at Stanford we
have the center,

00:55:43.490 --> 00:55:45.500
which is the acronym CCARE.

00:55:45.500 --> 00:55:48.590
And we actually have developed a
compassion cultivation training

00:55:48.590 --> 00:55:50.200
program, which
has been validated

00:55:50.200 --> 00:55:51.690
in a variety of studies.

00:55:51.690 --> 00:55:53.700
And we also have
created something

00:55:53.700 --> 00:55:57.080
called the compassion skills
training program online,

00:55:57.080 --> 00:56:00.300
which can be used in
a variety of settings.

00:56:00.300 --> 00:56:02.115
In the business
environment, we know

00:56:02.115 --> 00:56:04.150
that the integration of
these types of practices

00:56:04.150 --> 00:56:07.580
have an effect, not only--
and again, multiple studies

00:56:07.580 --> 00:56:10.240
have shown this-- if you look
at a publicly traded company

00:56:10.240 --> 00:56:12.280
and the integration of
these types of practices,

00:56:12.280 --> 00:56:14.660
in terms of shareholder
value and productivity--

00:56:14.660 --> 00:56:15.750
that goes up.

00:56:15.750 --> 00:56:19.350
In terms of expenditures
on health care,

00:56:19.350 --> 00:56:23.020
in regard to these areas we were
talking about earlier, in terms

00:56:23.020 --> 00:56:28.540
of HR costs, because people
are not leaving the company,

00:56:28.540 --> 00:56:30.210
they're not not showing up.

00:56:33.331 --> 00:56:35.330
You know, there's this
thing called absenteeism,

00:56:35.330 --> 00:56:37.204
but there's also a thing
called presenteeism.

00:56:37.204 --> 00:56:37.900
Right?

00:56:37.900 --> 00:56:40.770
You're here, but
you're not here.

00:56:40.770 --> 00:56:45.290
And so then if you look in
the social justice arena,

00:56:45.290 --> 00:56:47.980
we have a disaster in the
juvenile justice system.

00:56:47.980 --> 00:56:49.540
We have a militarized
police force.

00:56:49.540 --> 00:56:50.570
Right?

00:56:50.570 --> 00:56:52.560
Those are not
compassionate environments.

00:56:52.560 --> 00:56:54.390
But we know-- and
we were just talking

00:56:54.390 --> 00:56:55.600
about-- what was her name?

00:56:55.600 --> 00:56:57.730
Bedi?

00:56:57.730 --> 00:57:01.890
Kiran Bedi, who from India--
she integrated these types

00:57:01.890 --> 00:57:03.359
of practices into
the prison system

00:57:03.359 --> 00:57:04.400
in the police department.

00:57:04.400 --> 00:57:06.560
Had a profound, profound
impact-- to the point

00:57:06.560 --> 00:57:08.030
that they require it.

00:57:08.030 --> 00:57:09.510
That's what we need to do here.

00:57:09.510 --> 00:57:11.180
And in fact, I'm
the vice chairman

00:57:11.180 --> 00:57:14.200
of an entity called the
Charter for Compassion.

00:57:14.200 --> 00:57:16.379
And there's a compassionate
cities movement.

00:57:16.379 --> 00:57:18.420
And the mayor of Louisville--
believe it or not--

00:57:18.420 --> 00:57:23.100
Louisville, a bastion
of blue and red,

00:57:23.100 --> 00:57:25.047
he's integrating all of
these types of things

00:57:25.047 --> 00:57:27.630
into the business environment,
educational environment, health

00:57:27.630 --> 00:57:29.350
care system, all of these.

00:57:29.350 --> 00:57:33.220
And the police system and
the juvenile justice--

00:57:33.220 --> 00:57:35.020
and very, very positive impact.

00:57:35.020 --> 00:57:38.360
In fact, he was re-elected
without an opponent based

00:57:38.360 --> 00:57:42.880
simply on being compassionate.

00:57:42.880 --> 00:57:45.060
That is the power of this.

00:57:45.060 --> 00:57:46.920
So again, to
emphasize, each of us

00:57:46.920 --> 00:57:49.870
has within our ability to
profoundly affect not only

00:57:49.870 --> 00:57:53.540
ourselves but
everyone around us.

00:57:53.540 --> 00:57:55.540
So thank you again.

